For Rabbi Eliezer, who was contemporary with Rabbi J oshua, if he did not live before him, asserts that a proselyte cir- cumcised and not baptized, was a true proselyte, for so we read of the patriarchs Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob, that they were circum- cised, but not baptized. But Rabbi J oshua affirms, that he who was baptized, not he who was circumcised, was a true proselyte. To whom shall I give credit? To Eliezer, who asserts what the scripture confirms, or to Joshua, who affirms what is nowhere to be found in scripture? But the rabbins upheld Joshua‘s side, and what wonder was it? for it made for their business, that is, for the honour of the Jewish religion, that the Christians should borrow their ceremonies from them.
